# An integrative theory of attention-deficit/ hyperactivity  disorder based on the cognitive and affective neurosciences
**Autores**: JOEL T. NIGG, B. J. CASEY
**Año**: 1997
**Journal**: Scientific Paper
**DOI/Link**: N/A

## Abstract
Abstract
Attention-deficit0hyperactivity disorder ~ADHD! is a behavioral syndrome that arises in early childhood, often
co-occurs with conduct disorder and leads, developmentally, to antisocial behavior and substance abuse. Models
from cognitive and affective neuroscience have been invoked in an effort to understand the development of ADHD,
leading to a broad array of interrelated theories and hypothesized mechanisms. In this paper, we highlight core
mechanisms that may cut across several theories and constructs, and thus provide some leverage for further study
and conceptualization from a neuroscience perspective. We emphasize the joint operations of frontostriatal and
frontocerebellar neural loops in detecting and predicting what and when important events in the environment will
occur and their interaction with frontoamygdala loops in assigning emotional significance to these events. We note
that weaknesses in the development of these basic operations could lead to decrement in the development of
cognitive and affective control and other mental operations mediated by prefrontal cortex during development. In
turn, such decrement could lead to many of the phenotypic cognitive and neuropsychological features seen in
children with ADHD.
Considerable overlap exists in neuroscience-
based theories of dysregulatory disorders such
as attention-deficit0hyperactivity disorder
~ADHD!, conduct disorder, alcoholism, and
substance abuse, from both cognitive and af-
fective perspectives. For example, various
operations subsumed under the concept of ex-
ecutive functions ~related to the cognitive
neuroscience concept of cognitive control! are
thought to be related toADHD ~Barkley, 1997!,
conduct disorder ~Seguin, Boulerice, Harden,
Tremblay, & Pihl, 1999!, alcoholism ~Nigg,
Glass, Wong, Poon, Jester, Fitzgerald, Puttler,
Adams, & Zucker, 2004; Pihl, Peterson, &
Finn, 1990!, and substance abuse0dependence
~Giancola & Tarter, 1999!. Likewise, dysfunc-
tional reinforcement responses in the brain
~related to affective response systems! are im-
plicated in ADHD ~Sagvolden, Aase, Zeiner,
& Berger, 1998!, conduct disorder0antisociality
~Gorenstein & Newman, 1980; Raine, 2002!,
alcoholism ~Finn, Mazas, Justus, & Stein-
metz, 2002!, and substance abuse. This over-
lap is not surprising, because ADHD and
antisocial behavior0conduct disorder co-occur
at high rates ~Hinshaw, 1987!. In addition,
both ADHD and conduct disorder and their
joint occurrence confer risk of future alcohol-
ism and substance abuse. Indeed, some theo-
rists have proposed that the same cognitive
and affective mechanisms underlie all of
the “dysregulatory” psychopathologies of hy-
peractivity, antisociality, substance abuse0
dependence, impulsive aggression, and mania
~Gorenstein & Newman, 1980!.
