However, clinical syndromes can be mean-
ingfully, if partially, discriminated in the case
of attention deficits0hyperactivity and con-
duct problems0aggression ~Hinshaw, 1987!.
Likewise, the neuroanatomical correlates of
these syndromes may be partially separable.
For example, problems in cognitive control
may predominate in ADHD, whereas deficits
in affective responding ~e.g., lack of fear con-
ditioning or anxiety! may better characterize a
subgroup with severe antisociality or psychop-
athy ~Lorber, 2004; Nigg, 2003!. Alterna-
tively, it may be that similar neural systems
~or the same psychological mechanisms! are
involved in these overlapping disorders, and
that the specific behavioral expression de-
pends on learning history or other moderators
during development.
It is not surprising that the neural systems
implicated in the various mechanism-based
theories of these impulse-control disorders
overlap as well. Executive functions, reward,
emotional regulation, and motivation, for ex-
ample, all involve closely related neuroana-
tomical circuits and neurochemistry. It
therefore may be possible to clarify our un-
derstanding of these mechanisms by drawing
upon insights from cognitive and affective
neuroscience, in conjunction with insights from
developmental psychopathology. In this arti-
cle, we emphasize behavioral regulation or
cognitive control, defined as the ability to sup-
press inappropriate behaviors in response to
contextual and temporal cues and adjust be-
havior accordingly. We consider how cogni-
tive control may be related to affective
response, and how both may be developmen-
tally related to ADHD, which serves as our
exemplar impulse-control0regulatory disorder.
Advances in neuroimaging tools and the
growing integration of cognitive and affective
neuroscience provide a fresh opportunity to
describe the neurobiological basis of the cog-
nitive and affective processes implicated in
ADHD. A cognitive and affective neurosci-
ence approach provides the opportunity to re-
fine conceptions of these impulse-related
psychopathologies and sharpen and clarify the
core mechanisms that may cut across some of
these diverse syndromes. We focus on ADHD
while recognizing the likelihood of some over-
lap in our logic with what may be claimed
about other, perhaps related, impulse-control
disorders.
ADHD Phenotypic Features and
Neuroanatomic Correlates
Clinical phenotype
We begin by briefly describing the phenotype
to be explained. ADHD is an early-emerging
behavioral syndrome, usually apparent by age
6 or 7 years, but thought to have develop-
mental precursors much earlier than that. It is
characterized by developmentally excessive
activity, impulsivity, and disorganized, off-
task behaviors. Hallmark behaviors include
going off task with speech or activity, losing
things, and having trouble staying organized,
not seeming to pay attention to what is being
said or done, excess activity ~in children, run-
ning around “as if driven by a motor”!, loud,
reckless play, and impulsive, even dangerous
behavior ~e.g., blurting out something that
should not be said; darting out into traffic
without looking!. As a result of these behav-
iors, children with ADHD are far more likely
than nondisordered children to fall behind in
school, to be suspended or expelled, to be
rejected by peers and have few friends, and
to be at risk for accidents and physical inju-
ries ~Hinshaw, 2002!. The syndrome is more
common in boys, at least in childhood, and
relatively persistent, with a majority continu-
ing to have some impairment into adoles-
cence and a substantial percentage continuing
to do so into adulthood ~Mannuzza & Klein,
2000!. These later impairing problems can
include excess traffic accidents, marital prob-
lems, employment difficulties, injuries, as
well as antisocial behaviors, alcohol and
substance abuse and dependence, and aggres-
sion ~Barkley, Murphy, & Kwasnik, 1996a,
1996b!.
Groups of individuals diagnosed with
ADHD are heterogeneous. DSM-IV specifies
three subtypes: primarily inattentive, primar-
ily hyperactive–impulsive, and combined ~both
inattentive and hyperactive–impulsive!. Our
focus in this paper is primarily on the ADHD-
786
J. T. Nigg and B. J. Casey
combined type.1 Yet, even within that sub-
type, variation is noteworthy. For example,
affectively, a subgroup has prominent mood
or anxiety problems, which co-occur above
chance with ADHD; another subgroup has ab-
normal low anxiety and is at risk of severe
antisociality. Cognitively, only some show
characteristic impairments on a given neuro-
psychological measure, as discussed in detail
by Nigg, Willcutt, Doyle, and Sonuga–Barke
~2005!. Neuroanatomically, hypoplasias of key
brain structures, which we detail later, are
likely to be identifiable, but only in a subset.
Thus, cognitive, neuroanatomical, or physio-
logical measures are not diagnostic at present.
Moreover, family history varies within these
samples, as do other contextual correlates. In
short, genetic, neurobiological, and etiologi-
cal heterogeneity are virtually assured.
Despite the problem of heterogeneity, the
literature admits of several clear group trends
that can guide theorizing and application of
neuroscience to the syndrome. Any such ac-
count may, in the end, account for a particular
subset of the population with this behavioral
phenotype. Yet, such accounts need to be de-
veloped so that those subgroups can eventu-
ally be properly identified and the diagnostic
nosology refined in relation to etiological
mechanisms.
Neurocognitive phenotype
The behavioral, cognitive, and neuropsycho-
logical phenotype of ADHD is relatively well
characterized at this point. Thus, we know
that, as a group, children with ADHD exhibit
a range of context-dependent characteristic re-
sponses that cannot be fully explained by co-
morbid psychopathology ~Nigg, Hinshaw,
Carte, & Treuting, 1998; Nigg, Stavro, Etten-
hofer, Hambrick, Miller, & Henderson, in
press!: ~a! in slow, careful contexts, responses
are hasty and inaccurate or inappropriate ~clin-
ically defined “impulsivity”!; ~b! in fast, ac-
curate contexts, responses are slow and
inaccurate ~the “underaroused” hallmark; Oos-
terlaan, Logan, & Sergeant, 1998!; ~c! in fast
decision contexts, the ability to interrupt a pre-
potent or prepared response is impaired ~faulty
“executive response inhibition”; Barkley, 1997;
Logan, 1994; Nigg, 1999, 2001!; ~d! when
complex organization of response is required,
executive functioning is impaired, in the form
of faulty planning, working memory, and in-
tegration ~Barkley, 1997; Pennington & Ozo-
noff, 1996; Willcutt, Doyle, Nigg, Farone, &
Pennington, in press!; ~e! in the presence of
cues for reward or incentive, delay of reward
is difficult, and immediate rewards are given
disproportionate weight over larger but later
rewards ~Luman et al., 2005!; and ~f! tempo-
ral information processing is affected, with a
tendency to overestimate time intervals ~Bark-
ley, Murphy, & Bush, 2001; Toplak, Ruck-
lidge, Hetherington, John, & Tannock, 2003!,
a historical hallmark of impulsivity now being
integrated with neuroscience theories ~Castel-
lanos & Tannock, 2002!.
Several neurocognitive process theories
have been developed to try to account both for
the symptomatic behavior of individuals with
ADHD, and for the preceding profile of cog-
nitive and affective weaknesses, nearly all ad-
dressing aspects of self regulation in some
form ~Barkley, 1997; MacCoon, Wallace, &
Newman, 2004; Sagvolden, Johansen, Aase,
& Russell, 2005; Sergeant, Oosterlaan, & van
der Meere, 1999!. On the one hand, then,
neuroscience has influencedADHD theory sub-
stantially already ~Barkley, 1997; Berger &
Posner, 2000; Castellanos & Tannock, 2002;
Pennington & Ozonoff, 1996; Sagvolden et al.,
2005!. On the other hand, theories remain rel-
atively unintegrated from a cognitive and af-
fective neuroscience point of view ~Berger &
Posner, 2000; Castellanos & Tannock, 2002!.
Furthermore, the developmental account in
most theories is limited with regard to the
interdependence of respective neural systems
and cognitive abilities. We focus on how cog-
nitive and affective neuroscience can help de-
