Neurodevelopment and ADHD
Development of the neural systems that sup-
portself-regulation~andareinvolvedinADHD!,
is expected to feature at least two key princi-
pals. The first is the mutual influence of com-
ponents of regulatory control on one another
during development, including the scaffolding
of later abilities onto earlier abilities, assisted
by the socialization context. Because of the im-
portance of social interactions in this develop-
ment, we often choose social interaction
examples to illustrate our points later. Second,
neural organization is expected to reflect in-
creasing specialization during development in
childhoodashigherordercognitiveabilitiestake
hold ~Johnson, 2001!. Indeed, neural develop-
ment of the cortical and subcortical pathways,
at issue here, continues as late as early adult-
hoodintheformofcontinuedmyelination,prun-
ing,andspecializationofcircuitry~Benes,2001;
Casey, Tottenham, Liston, & Durston, 2005;
Gogtayetal.,2004;Sowell,Thompson,Holmes,
Jernigan, & Toga, 1999; Sowell, Thompson,
Leonard,Welcome, Kan, &Toga, 2004!.These
processes mature at different rates in different
cortical and subcortical areas, with the regions
of prefrontal cortex most important for cogni-
tive control completing synaptic specializa-
tion the latest ~Bourgeois, Goldman–Rakic, &
Rakic,1994;Huttonlocher&Dabholkar,1997!.
Among the core computational mechanisms
at issue here, the ability to predict temporal
and contextual structure in the environment
is central. This ability develops as early as in-
fancy, as evidenced by infant looking times to
eventsthatviolatetheirimplicitpredictions~Saf-
fran, Aslin, & Newport, 1996!. However, the
ancillary ability to deliberately alter behavior
in response to cues or unexpected events may
notemergeuntiltoddlerhood~Rothbart&Bates,
1998!, as evidenced by toddler’s ability to vol-
untarily override a cue to calm their own mood.
This ability becomes refined with age in the
cognitive domain as shown recently by Rueda,
Fan,McCandliss,Halparin,Gruber,Lercari,and
Posner ~2004!, who found that by age 7 years,
attentional responses could be redirected from
competing sources to the relevant one.
With development, these cognitive and neu-
ral systems become more differentiated as they
are modulated both by experience and by the
maturation of top-down cortical projections
from prefrontal cortex that help the child alter
behavior to achieve a goal when these predic-
tions are violated. This increasing differentia-
tion is observed, for example, when a simple
ability to wait a short time for a reward ~the
toddlerorpreschoolerwhomanagestowaitqui-
etly in anticipation of dessert! develops into the
abilitytoplanandcarryoutseveralself-directed
steps to realize a goal ~as when a 10-year-old
child assembles a model airplane or plans an
elaborate game of house with her friends!.
Early infant and toddler abilities to orient
attention, respond to cues, and control their
behavior may be framed as precursors to the
mature development of ~a! reflexive orienting
~“where” orienting!, guided by a parietal–
thalamic circuit; ~b! alerting and vigilance
~“when” orienting!, guided by noradrenergic
activation of right-lateralized circuitry includ-
ing the cerebellar–cortical circuits; ~c! re-
inforcement learning and reward response,
guided by frontolimbic circuitry; and ~d! ef-
fortful regulation and voluntary planning of
behavior and cognition, which involves fron-
tostriatal circuitry.2 The latter two systems,
which both rely heavily on frontostriatal loops
and dopaminergic modulation, may be consid-
ered to share the property of altering actions
when expectations ~predictions! are violated
as to “what” is presented.
Of these basic circuits, three appear to be
involved relatively more in the case of ADHD.
Evidence for the involvement of the posterior
reflexive orienting system has generally been
negative ~see meta-analysis by Huang–Pollock
& Nigg, 2003!. Thus children with ADHD
2. Some theorists believe motor circuitry is also involved
in ADHD; in the interest of space, we do not explore
that literature in this paper. For further

