## Results
results in weakened ability to carry out
actions that must be represented in working
memory, that require monitoring of new infor-
mation, and that require holding multiple goals
in mind. This model is consistent with our
hypothesis of the way in which the prefrontal
cortex, basal ganglia, and cerebellum are in-
volved in the suppression of inappropriate
thoughts and behaviors. This view of cogni-
tive control also is consistent with some oth-
ers that specify the role of the basal ganglia in
interrupting behavior ~Kimberg & Farrah,
1998!, but it contrasts with still other cogni-
tive theories that emphasize the role of ventral
and orbital prefrontal cortex in inhibitory func-
tions ~Diamond, 1990; Iversen & Mishkin,
1970!.
In turn, if the basal ganglia are injured, we
would expect the child to either have diffi-
culty in ~a! suppressing competing behaviors
ADHD and current neuroscience models
793
during goal-directed activity, and0or ~b! accu-
rately predicting the likely results of their ac-
tions in a real situation ~as opposed to a
hypothetical situation! and thus in choosing
an appropriate action in response to these cues
from peers, teachers, and parents. Finally, if
the cerebellum is affected, we would expect
difficulty in ~c! accurately predicting when
behaviors should change. For example, the
child in the classroom may continue to clown
around telling jokes even though the bell has
rung to indicate that it is time to settle down
and begin school work, because she has mis-
judged the implicit temporal window allowed
by the teacher for children to settle immedi-
ately after the bell.3
To summarize and recapitulate: how might
breakdowns in frontostriatal and0or fronto-
cerebellar circuitry contribute to the symp-
toms and behaviors observed in a disorder
such as ADHD? Assuming that frontostriatal
and frontocerebellar pathways serve to re-
cruit top-down control when detecting changes
in the environment, then their disruption may
result in inefficient prefrontal recruitment in
shifting and maintaining a behavioral set in
different contexts. This might appear as poor
sustained attention to multistep or complex
tasks ~because the expected changes in the
context as the task unfolds would not be com-
puted efficiently!, slow response in rapid
decision contexts ~because the system is in-
efficient at computing new information!, dif-
ficulty efficiently shifting from one response
set to another, and inefficient response to
changing reward or learning contexts, all of
which are consistent with the behavioral pro-
file of ADHD. More speculatively, early dis-
ruption of these mechanisms may lead to
inefficiencies in learning and socialization dur-
ing development, hampering the normal con-
solidation of self-regulation. For example, to
benefit from parental attunement, reflection,
explanation, or correction, the young child
has to accurately link the response to her own
behavior. This linkage then enables the child
to further strengthen their learning and self-
regulation abilities. Inefficiency in this link
may lead to failure to benefit from the “ex-
pectable” amount of parental correction, guid-
ance, or discipline.4
The proposed model implies an important
mutual-influence process in which intact cer-
ebellar and basal ganglia activation depends
on “expectable” prefrontal cortical responsiv-
ity, and vice versa. Thus, breakdowns in a
prefrontal cortex system could lead to mal-
adaptation of behaviors that depend on the
exquisite recognition and timing of predic-
tion violations in the environment, the latter
depending on cerebellar0basal ganglia opera-
tions. In this instance, we might expect over-
activity of these subcortical structures in a
maladaptive response. Conversely, atypical de-
velopment of cerebellar and0or basal ganglia
neural pathways could disrupt adaptive oper-
ation of prefrontally, goal-directed behavior
~i.e., cognitive control!.
Frontoamygdala circuitry in affect
regulation
Although affect-related frontoamygdala cir-
cuits have received comparatively less atten-
tion to date in biological theories of ADHD,
affect regulation, motivation, and reactive re-
sponse are quite important to the disorder. For
3. MacCoon et al. ~2004! propose a related concept of
behavioral regulation in their theory of psychopathy,
in which impulsive behavior is driven by failure to
detect cues that should lead to interruption of behav-
ior, that is, by a failure of selective attention. That
view is somewhat consistent with ours. However, in
our account, that failure of cue detection is due not to
an attentional failure, but to a failure to set up the
appropriate predictions when launching the behavioral
sequence. Because the predictions are not in place, the
significance of the cue is lost and behavior cannot be
adjusted.
4. This account is similar to that by Sagvolden and col-
leagues ~2005!. However, although they argue that
socialization breaks down in ADHD because of a steep
temporal gradient between behavior and consequence
~thus, consequences too far out in time, yet within the
average expectable window for child development,
fail to get incorporated into learning!, we are further
suggesting that failure to accurately predict the possi-
ble consequences of a behavior results in inefficient
computations when consequences do occur, so that the
system fails to incorporate this new information. The
view of Sagvolden et al., however, is compatible with
our view.
794
J. T. Nigg and B. J. Casey
example, there is increasing recognition that
in addition to their difficulties with impulsive
behavior, children with ADHD ~and other
impulse-control disorders! also have diffi-
culty with anger, mood, and affect regulation
~Pliszka, Carlson, & Swanson, 1999!, an ob-
servation that is completely congruent with
the integrated neural circuitry we are describ-
ing. Indeed, emotional context affects the re-
cruitment of cognitive control, and a substantial
literature investigates problems with approach
or avoidance related processes in ADHD ~Lu-
man, Oosterlaan, & Sergeant, 2005!. There-
fore, an account of affective neural circuitry is
essential to a complete portrayal of the neuro-
science of ADHD and its clinical and comor-
bid features.
At the most basic level, positive emotional
valence ~or expectation of reward! is related to
approach, whereas negative valence ~or expec-
tation of nonreward! is associated with avoid-
anceandwithdrawal~Davidson,Ekman,Saron,
Senulis, & Friesen, 1990; Hare,Tottenham, Da-
vidson,Glover,&Casey,2005;O’Doherty,Win-
ston, Critchley, Perrett, Burt, & Dolan, 2003!.
Thus, interactions between cognitive and emo-
tional processes play an important role in reg-
ulation of behavior in different incentive
contexts.Although the neural basis of these in-
teractions is not yet understood, reciprocal neu-
ralconnectionsexistbetweenprefrontalcontrol
regions and subcortical regions involved in af-
fective response ~Amaral, 1986; Groenewe-
gen, Berendse, & Haber, 1993; Ghashghaei &
Barbas, 2002; Haber, Groenewegen, Grove, &
Nauta, 1985; Haber, Kunishio, Mizobuchi, &
Lynd–Balta, 1995!.Animal studies have shown
the importance of the ventral striatum in appe-
titive~approach!conditioning~Garcia,Vouimba,
Baudry, & Thompson, 1999; LeDoux, 1995;
Parkinson, Cardinal, & Everitt, 2000; Parkin-
son,Dalley,Cardinal,Bamford,Fehnert,Lache-
nal, Rudarakanchana, Halkerston, Robbins, &
Everitt, 2002! and of the amygdala in aversive
~avoidance! conditioning. The ventral amyg-
dala in particular has been implicated in fear
conditioning and evaluating the emotional sig-
nificance of a stimulus ~LeDoux, 1998!.
Human neuroimaging studies of affective
control parallel the animal findings and show
a role for top-down prefrontal modulation of
subcortical regions ~Hariri, Bookheimer, &
Mazziotta, 2000; Hariri, Mattay, Tessitore,
Fera, & Weinberger, 2003; Keightley, Win-
ocur, Graham, Mayberg, Hevenor, & Grady,
2003; Nomura, Ohira, Haneda, Iidaka, Sa-
dato, Okada, & Yonekura, 2004; Ochsner, Ray,
Cooper, Robertson, Chopra, Gabrieli, & Gross,
2004!. These studies show greater activation
in the ventral amygdala when approaching neg-
ative information ~i.e., fearful faces; Hare et al.,
2005; Thomas, Hunt, Vizueta, Sommer, Dur-
ston, Yang, & Worden, 2004!. The greater the
amygdala activity, the slower the reaction times
in detecting ~approaching! negative informa-
tion ~e.g., fearful faces; Hare et al., 2005!.
Positive emotional stimuli influence behavior
and neural activity differently ~Hare et al.,
2005!. Compared to fearful expressions, happy
expressions elicit greater activity in the nu-
cleus accumbens, a region associated with
reward and appetitive behavior ~Nestler,
2004; Schultz, Tremblay, & Hollerman, 2000!.
Therefore, activation of the amygdala is asso-
ciated with avoidance of potentially unpleas-
ant events, while activation of the nucleus
accumbens is related to approaching a poten-
tially positive event. Previous imaging studies
have shown an inverse correlation between
prefrontal cortical activation and amygdala ac-
tivity, which can be interpreted as reflecting
top-down modulation of emotional processes
~Drevets & Raichle, 1998!. More recently, Hare
and colleagues ~2005! reported an inverse cor-
relation between ventral striatum and amyg-
dala activation, such that the activity of one
inhibits or suppresses the other ~Hare & Ca-
sey, 2005!.
We now extend an affective component to
our model of prefrontal modulation of subcor-
tical systems in behavioral regulation. Signals
to the prefrontal cortex from the ventral stria-
tum enhance the tendency to approach posi-
tive ~reward related or reinforcing! stimuli.
Signaling from the ventral amygdala, in con-
trast, would invoke avoidance behavior ~cue
for nonreward cues!. These signals then must
be integrated with the existing behavior ~goal
directed or otherwise! of the child. Thus, when
emotional information is irrelevant or con-
trary to the current goal, top-down connec-
tions from the prefrontal cortex to subcortical
ADHD and current neuroscience models
795
regions are critical for regulating the effects
of affective information on behavior. Their
ability to do so obviously depends both on
the integrity of those top-down systems and
on the intensity or strength of the affective
response.
It is straightforward to imagine that impul-
sivity could result from unregulated approach
to almost any potential reward, as well as from
failure to avoid potential punishment. Histor-
ically, theories of impulsivity have often
pointed to such possibilities, especially in con-
junction with impaired frontal cortical func-
tion ~Gray, 1971!. For example, excess reward
response easily translates, conceptually, into
ill-conceived impulsive acts. If a child is work-
ing on his homework in class, but sees his
friend leave his seat to sharpen a pencil, he
may see the potential immediate reward in
leaving his own seat to go and interact with
his friend. If prefrontal modulation is weak,
he may fail to hold in mind the goal of finish-
ing his test preparation so that he can pass the
test and earn the parental reward of spending
the entire day with his friend this weekend.
Impulsive behavior in defeat of the long-
range goal results, as he leaves his seat and
ultimately loses his weekend privilege.
Thus, it is rather straightforward to begin
to imagine how these affective systems could
contribute to ADHD, at least to its impulsive
features. Others have developed this idea be-
fore, and the role of excessive approach re-
sponding in particular ~i.e., overvaluing of
immediate reward cues! is widely discussed
in the ADHD literature ~Douglas, 1989; Haen-
lein & Caul, 1987; Sagvolden et al., 1998,
2005!. Clearly, a tendency to overweight im-
mediate rewards could lead to failure to con-
sider long-term consequences sufficiently,
emanating in impulsive behaviors ~the child
leaves his seat, gets held after school, is un-
able to see his friend that weekend!.
Likewise, failure of avoidance learning can,
in principal, result in continuing to engage in
behavior even when it is about to lead to neg-
ative consequences, which could have been
predicted based on past event frequencies and
timing, but this time because the negative va-
lence is insufficiently weighted ~i.e., the child
fails to experience adequate anxiety when the
teacher gives a warning, or is unaffected emo-
tionally by the punishment or expulsion, so
the behavior continues!. Many impulsive and
socially ineffective behaviors of individuals
with ADHD could conceivably fit in one of
these categories.
However, the empirical data in support of
these “single vector” affective explanations of
impulsivity inADHD are rather weak.We com-
ment briefly on each of these points. First, how
likelyisitthatADHDcanbeunderstoodinlight
of an excess approach response or inadequate
modulationofapproachtendencies?Onesource
of support for this view would come from stud-
ies that suggest that temperament or personal-
ity traits associated with approach ~e.g.,
Extraversion or positive affectivity! are asso-
ciated withADHD. Studies on this question are
few, and results are admittedly mixed ~Nigg,
John, Blaskey, Huang–Pollock, Willcutt, Hin-
shaw, & Pennington, 2002!. Nigg, Blaskey,
Huang–Pollock, and John ~2002! found that
ADHD was associated in most cases with low
scores on the personality trait of constraint ~as-
sociatedconceptuallywiththefrontostriatalcir-
cuitrywedescribedearlier!,butthatonlyasmall
subgroup was associated with very high extra-
version scores.
Efforts to assess reaction time and accu-
racy responses in relation to cues for reward
in ADHD have yielded mixed findings as well
~Iaboni, Douglas, & Baker, 1995!, perhaps in
part due to failure to control for conduct dis-
order and in part due to varying ages of sam-
ples. Physiological measures ~e.g., heart rate
response to cues for reward! have also shown
an inconsistent picture ~Iaboni, Douglas, &
Ditto, 1997; Pliszka, Hatch, Borcherding, &
Rogeness, 1993!, although some support can
be found. On balance, despite some support-
ive evidence, it seems likely that excess
approach tendencies cannot by themselves ac-
count for ADHD ~for a review, see Luman
et al., 2005!.
Second, how readily can ADHD be viewed
as insufficient avoidance response ~Quay,
1988!? Most performance-based research has
failed to support the idea that children with
ADHD are insensitive to cues for nonreward
~Iaboni et al., 1995; for a review, see Nigg,
2001!, although some physiological studies
796
J. T. Nigg and B. J. Casey
appear supportive. In contrast, an impaired
avoidance response may be a feature of impul-
sive behavior in some cases of unsocialized
conduct disorder and0or psychopathy ~New-
man & Wallace, 1993; Raine, 2002!. This, in
turn, would implicate a subset of children with
ADHD with low anxiety and high aggression,
who go on to develop these more serious prob-
lems characterized by primary disturbance of
this affective response systems.
In short, it appears that support is incom-
plete at best for these two “single vector” at-
tempts to explain ADHD via a breakdown in
affective response neural systems. A more
promising approach may be the recognition
that ADHD can arise from discrete routes, but
given the “crosstalk” among the neural cir-
cuits ~Haber, 2003!, may reflect the joint op-
eration of the systems. The goal-directed
behaviors that we have described in this paper
and that appear disrupted in ADHD require
continual processing of ongoing and complex
chains of events. This updating of goal states
in the context of the frequency, timing, and
emotional valence of information can be re-
flected in the neural circuitry. Information can
thus be channeled from limbic to cognitive
and to motor circuits at the subcortical level,
allowing for appropriate responses to environ-
mental cues. Parallel circuits must work to-
gether, so that the coordinated behaviors are
maintained, but also can be modified and
changed according to the particular context
and whether it was expected or not. The in-
ability to protect specific actions related to
later goals, or to adapt effectively to new en-
vironment cues, are core features of ADHD
that can be reflected in the previously de-
scribed neural circuitry that supports aspects
of motor control, cognition, and motivation.
Summary, Consolidation, and Key Issues
Developmental pathways to ADHD
Collectively, this review of key clinical symp-
toms and the implicated neuroanatomical cir-
cuits indicates that prefrontal projections are a
critical aspect of the basic elements of cogni-
tive and affective control that are involved in
ADHD. Developmental changes in prefrontal
circuitry contribute to the emergence of ma-
ture cognitive control as well as well-regulated
affective response. Therefore, development
must be considered in delineating the contri-
butions of different brain regions ~e.g., pre-
frontal cortex, striatum, cerebellum, amygdala!
to cognitive and affective control as relevant
to impulsive or dysregulatory psychopathol-
ogy generally and ADHD in particular. Given
the protracted maturation of prefrontal cortex
relative to subcortical regions, one would ex-
pect to see a shift from greater activity in
subcortical regions like the amygdala and nu-
cleus accumbens in childhood to increased pre-
frontally mediated processing in adults. A
developmental delay view of ADHD may im-
plicate such further protracted development
of these systems.
An integrated cognitive and affective neuro-
science understanding of ADHD would ide-
ally consider components of cognitive control,
affect regulation, and their mutual influence
on one another in behavioral regulation and in
development. An important principal that we
noted earlier is that these systems support one
another ~or fail to do so! during early devel-
opment. Because temperament can be thought
of as implicating affective regulation, early
temperamental predispositions may represent
precursors to difficulty with cognitive control
or affective ~reactive! intensity ~Rothbart &
Bates, 1998!. For example, very early in life
infants can be reliably coded as tending to
strongly approach novel stimuli ~associated
with weak physiological reactivity to those
situations!, versus tending to strongly with-
draw ~associated with strong physiological re-
activity!; the same features can be reliably
coded in toddlers and preschoolers placed in a
room with unfamiliar children ~Kagan, 2003;
Kagan, Reznick, & Snidman, 1987!.
Similarly, toddlers can be reliably assessed
in relation to their temperamental ability to
deliberately redirect attention ~Rothbart &
Bates, 1998!, a possible precursor to top-
down cognitive control that may be indicative
of successful prediction mechanisms. By con-
trast, these predispositions likely influence one
another and are influenced by socialization
during the toddler and preschool years, culmi-
nating in relatively stable patterns of behavior
ADHD and current neuroscience models
797
by the early elementary school years that en-
able characterization of behavioral syndromes
such as ADHD.
Different types of temperamental tenden-
cies may lead to ADHD, and ADHD itself
then may represent the common final out-
come of a discrete handful of developmental
pathways, when viewed from the perspective
of cognitive and affective neuroscience. Draw-
ing upon principals of developmental psycho-
pathology, this situation could exemplify
equifinality ~Cicchetti & Rogosch, 1996! in
that somewhat distinct breakdowns in neural
processing systems lead to a common behav-
ioral phenotype. We summarize this state of
affairs in Figure 2a. It illustrates that several
types of breakdown in the prediction and learn-
ing circuits that underlie cognitive control
might nonetheless result in similar surface
symptoms at the level of ratings or observa-
tions of children’s molar behavior.
Alternatively, and what we think is more
likely, is that in addition to some equifinality,
ADHD also exemplifies multiple pathways
with somewhat different phenotypic outcomes
that are still in the process of being validated
as distinct etiological subgroups. We summa-
rize these various pathways in Figure 2b.
As it suggests, one route to ADHD might
be via ~a! breakdown in fundamental pre-
diction mechanisms as we described earlier,
leading secondarily to problems in cognitive
Figure 2. A schematic illustration of the pathways to ADHD symptoms and syndrome: ~a! equifinality
in ADHD and neuroscience-based hypothesized computational mechanism breakdowns and ~b! multiple
pathways to related but partially distinct etiological phenotypes in ADHD.
798
J. T. Nigg and B. J. Casey
control, “executive functioning,” with second-
ary problems in arousal regulation and affect
regulation due to weakness in the “top-down”
regulatory system. If this route was accom-
panied by relatively intact affect response
systems, then the clinical picture might be rel-
atively benign: it might yield ADHD charac-
terized by ineffective, disorganized behavior,
but without the severe comorbid picture that
emerges when affective systems also break
down.
Another route might be via primary dys-
function in the affective ~b! approach or ~c!
avoidance systems. These routes may lead
to somewhat different clinical phenotypes.
For example, as noted, we suspect that faulty
avoidance learning ~characterized by lack of
skin conductance responses to cues for nonre-
ward or punishment!, relatively well charac-
terized in severe psychopathy or unsocialized
conduct disorder, is a feature of impulsive0
antisocial behavior ~bottom route, Figure 2b!.
This route represents another subgroup of chil-
dren with impulsive behavior problems, most
of whom may initially be viewed clinically as
having ADHD. However, they will go on to
aggressive0or antisocial behaviors in many in-
stances ~for simplicity, we are omitting here
discussion of the extensively described social-
ization experiences that moderate, mediate, and
maintain that developmental pathway; see Sny-
der, Reid, & Patterson, 2003!. The result would
be that this pathways often yields a relatively
severely disturbed group of youngsters with
problems in impulsivity, aggression, social ad-
aptation, and affective response, who are at
risk for severe antisocial outcomes or psychop-
athy ~Pliszka et al., 1999; Simonoff, Elander,
Holmshaw, Pickles, Murray, & Rutter, 2004!.
Still another possibility is that ADHD could
emerge simply via extreme approach tenden-
cies ~i.e., extreme temperamental approach,
probably related neurobiologically to reactiv-
ity of nucleus accumbens and associated cir-
cuitry as described earlier!. This route might
correspond to problems in reinforcement learn-
ing as described by Sagvolden et al. ~2005!.
This pathway is illustrated in the middle route
in Figure 2b. This group may have minimal
cognitive problems and may not exhibit dif-
ficulties in “executive functioning,” cogni-
tive control, or related measures. Nigg,
Willcutt, Doyle, and Sonuga–Barke ~2005!
provide a discussion of the possibility that
only some children with ADHD are charac-
terized by neuropsychological executive func-
tion problems. Thus, this route as well may,
in many instances, be relatively benign in its
clinical course despite leading to diagnosis
and to impairment at least early in develop-
ment. Early emerging temperament traits thus
may indicate precursors to eventual develop-
ment of ADHD and map onto particular neu-
ral systems that may be involved in the
disorder.
However, a further and more nuanced pos-
sibility bears consideration. That is that dif-
ferent components of the ADHD phenotype
may be related to breakdowns in different neu-
ral circuits, but which then tend to co-occur
in their breakdown more often than chance,
leading to the observed syndrome of ADHD.
One model ~e.g., Sonuga–Barke, 2002! is that
the inattention disorganization symptoms of
ADHD are related to breakdown in cognitive
control ~response inhibition, or executive func-
tions!, whereas the impulsive symptoms of
ADHD are related to breakdowns in affective
responding ~primarily in a poorly regulated
approach system!. This state of affairs can be
visualized by considering the first two path-
ways in Figure 2b, not as distinct syndrome
outcomes, but as dimensional behavioral
domains.
Empirical tests of this possibility have been
few. However, Nigg et al. ~in press! created a
latent “executive” or “control” variable using
several clinical executive function tasks ~in-
cluding the stopping task, the Trailmaking Test,
the Tower of London, and the Wisconsin Card
Sort!. They then regressed this score on la-
tent variables for symptoms of inattention–
disorganization
~pooled
from
multiple
informants! and impulsivity–hyperactivity.
Only inattention–disorganization was uniquely
related to the executive score, roughly con-
gruent with our broad domain of cognitive
control and consistent with our two-pathway
model ~Figure 2b!.
Consistent with that finding, but approach-
ing the question from a personality0tempera-
mentperspective,Nigg,John,etal.~2002!found
ADHD and current neuroscience models
799
that symptoms of inattention–disorganization
were related to low trait Constraint after par-
tialing hyperactivity–implusivity from scores
for inattention–disorganization. Conversely,
when inattention was partialed from impulsiv-
ity, the latter symptoms were related to high
trait hostility but not to Constraint. This find-
ing also is broadly consistent with the idea
that the hyperactivity–impulsivity dimension
may be related to breakdown in affective re-
sponse systems, whereas the inattention–
disorganization behavioral dimension may be
related to breakdowns in cognitive control
~including “what” and “when” prediction sys-
tems!. Because these neural systems are needed
in support of one another in day to day behav-
ioral regulation, these problems tend to co-
occur, and the integrated syndrome of ADHD
is the result. However, experimentally it may
be possible to partially dissociate these effects
as illustrated in the cited studies.
Key developmental issues in ADHD
neuroscience research
Self-regulation develops through mutual-
influence processes both at the level of inter-
dependent neural systems, and at the level of
socialization ~learning experiences! interact-
ing with neural development. Social inter-
actions help the developing nervous system
consolidate into adaptive and functional regu-
latory capability that is increasingly at the com-
mand of the child as she develops. At the same
time, neural development and maturation con-
tinue all the way into late adolescence in the
neural structures involved in ADHD. At the
neural level of analysis, evidence is converg-
ing on frontal–striatal0frontal–cerebellar cir-
cuitry as involved in ADHD.
These systems are involved in myriad self-
regulatory behaviors and functions that emerge
and consolidate throughout childhood and into
adolescence. They include some of the latest
maturing structures in the brain, and they in-
clude networks heavily dependent on catechol-
amines as well as GABAergic systems. As a
result, several related but distinct cognitive
process models of ADHD have been pro-
posed, addressing different elements of the
integrated self-regulatory system ~effortful con-
trol, response inhibition, arousal regulation,
activation, reinforcement response, temporal
information processing!. These different theo-
ries indicate that ADHD theory has already
begun to be influenced by cognitive and affec-
tive neuroscience.
At the same time, these theories may be
able to be simplified by considering that these
two main circuits ~frontal–striatal and frontal–
cerebellar! share an integrated role in “cog-
nitive control,” which requires expectation
matching as to when and what is going to
occur in response to a behavior. We have noted
the evidence that children with ADHD have
normally developed spatial orienting ~“where;”
Huang–Pollock & Nigg, 2003!, but poor alert-
ing ~“when”; see Brandeis, van Leeuwen,
Rubia, Vitacco, Steger, Pascual–Marqui, &
Steinhausen, 1998; Nigg, Swanson, & Hin-
shaw, 1997! and poor ability to adjust to new
information in rapid-response contexts ~Nigg,
1999; Schachar, Tannock, & Logan, 1993!,
consistent with involvement of these core func-
tional operations. Although this evidence is
thus beginning to converge in ways that are
quite promising, we close by noting two ma-
jor issues that confront these theories and the
scientific field going forward in neuroscience
research on ADHD.
One issue is the need for continued elabo-
ration of developmental dynamics at two key
developmental periods. The first period is the
rapid increasing specialization of neural net-
works during early to middle childhood, when
ADHD is usually emerging and diagnosed.
Failure of the normal process of specializa-
tion ~perhaps via experience-dependent arbo-
rization and pruning in prefrontal–basal ganglia
and cerebellar–cortical loops! may be related
to the difficulty in consolidating cognitive con-
trol that we think is contributing to at least
one major pathway ADHD. This is also a pe-
riod when cognitive control is rapidly emerg-
ing and consolidating. For example, effortful
control in the form of strategic attentional and
impulse control continues to develop through-
out childhood, yielding steady progress in the
ability to ignore competing stimulus-driven
responses over the second to fourth grade years
~Huang–Pollock, Carr, & Nigg, 2003! and the
ability to inhibit primary responses over the
800
J. T. Nigg and B. J. Casey
age period from about ages 5 to 7 and beyond
~Carver, Livesey, & Charles, 2001!. Likewise,
Rueda et al. ~2004! found that between ages 6
and 9 years the attentional selection network
showed development to about age 7, whereas
the alerting response continued to mature at
least through age 10.
ADHD probably emerges in relation to dif-
ferences or breakdowns in this developmental
progression during the early childhood years.
Wearesuggestingherethatthisbreakdownmay
be related to breakdown in the basic mecha-
nism of detecting what and when violations of
expectations occur.Apotential approach for ex-
amining these mechanisms in parallel is simi-
lar to an attention network task described by
Rueda et al. ~2004!, which measures alerting,
orienting,andconflictresolutionwithinthesame
task.We developed a visual detection task ~Da-
vidson, Horvitz, Tottenham, Durston, Fos-
sella, & Casey, 2003! wherein the predictability
of events is manipulated in two ways. Either an
expected or unexpected stimulus is presented
at either an expected or unexpected time. On
the majority of trials an expected event occurs
at the expected time for predictions to occur,
but for the conditions of interest either an un-
expected event occurred or an event occurred
at an unexpected time. Behavioral results using
this paradigm showed increased reaction times
and reduced accuracy for unexpected events,
consistent with the notion that control pro-
cesses may be needed to perform these trials.
Developmental data from 36 subjects show that
children perform worse than adolescents and
adults. Imaging data using this paradigm sug-
gested that the caudate nucleus appears to be
more sensitive to stimulus violations ~what!,
whereasthecerebellumismoresensitivetotem-
poral violations ~when! during performance of
this task. These results provide further evi-
dence for a functional distinction between fron-
tostriatal and frontocerebellar circuitry in the
humanbrainandsuggestthatthisparadigmmay
serve as an exemplar task for use with children
with ADHD to test our theory that basic stim-
ulus and temporal prediction mechanisms are
affected in ADHD.
To test the potential relevance of detecting
the emotional significance of predicted events,
the stimuli used in the paradigm could be emo-
tional in nature ~e.g., happy and fearful faces!.
This additional component to the task could
provide important information on how com-
peting limbic ~amygdala! and reward neural
systems ~nucleus accumbens! implicated in ap-
proach and avoidance behavior play a role in
the clinical phenotype of this disorder.
Another prediction that flows from our ar-
gument is that ADHD should be associated
with failures in implicit learning ~this has been
examined in only a limited number of studies,
usually involving patients with tic disorders
or obsessive–compulsive disorder; Channon,
Pratt, & Robertson, 2003!. Several paradigms
are available for such investigation. In all, we
are suggesting that modified experimental par-
adigms may be useful in elucidating particu-
lar mechanistic breakdowns inADHD, but that
these must be integrated with a developmental
account of how these mechanisms emerge and
influence one another during childhood.
Following that last point, a second key pe-
riod for developmental clarification is the
adolescent transition, when relevant neural net-
works are consolidating and maturing. The
ability to rapidly suppress unintended or pre-
potent responses continues to develop through
adolescence ~Bedard, Nichols, Barbosa,
Schachar, Logan, & Tannock, 2002!, presum-
ably aided by ongoing myelination and prun-
ing of frontal cortical neural networks ~Benes,
2001! in conjunction with socialization and
learning experiences. Symptomatically, in cases
of ADHD, hyperactivity tends to improve,
whereas impulsive and disorganized behav-
iors tend to become salient problems for chil-
dren withADHD in this developmental period.
In addition, gender ratios appear to shift, with
girls gaining in relative frequency of diagno-
sis. Hormonal effects may be important here
as well.
Progress on these fronts will ensue in part
from studies that examine developmental pro-
gressions in neural development ~e.g., brain
imaging over time; see Giedd, Vaituzis, Ham-
burger, Lange, Rajapakse, Kaysen, Vauss, &
Rapoport, 1996! in relation to changes in be-
havioral expression ~e.g., decrease versus
continuity in impulsivity in adolescence; wors-
ening of disorganization relative to peers in
early childhood and elementary school!. A key
ADHD and current neuroscience models
801
question here is the extent to which behaviors
that are developmentally normal at one age
~e.g., impulsive behavior at age 3 years! fail to
consolidate in the context of cognitive con-
trol, instead persisting until they are develop-
mentally inappropriate ~e.g., similar age 3-year
level impulsivity continuing at age 6 years!.
ADHD may in some cases reflect residual ac-
tivation patterns that fail to diminish with mat-
uration. However, at this point knowledge
about even the normal progression of and in-
dividual differences in the neural systems at
issue remains limited.
A second overarching issue that we high-
light here is heterogeneity, both in the path-
ways toADHD and in the phenotype ofADHD.
We have been careful to posit that the mecha-
nisms we are discussing likely apply to many
children with ADHD and may cut across to
include children with other disorders such as
some cases of conduct disorder ~most of which
also have ADHD!. However, multiple genetic
and other etiologies likely are involved in
ADHD. Individual differences in, for exam-
ple, neural development, have not begun to be
seriously explored in samples of children or
adults with ADHD.
A number of other issues in ADHD devel-
opment that could be related to neuroscience
have been bypassed here in the interest of brev-
ity. For example, literatures are beginning to
emerge in terms of differences betweenADHD
DSM-IVsubtypes,genderdifferencesinADHD
symptoms and in concomitant neural activa-
tion patterns, hormone effects on ADHD, and
the role of motor circuitry ~see footnote 2!. We
defer discussion of those topics.

## Clinical Significance
Conclusion
We sought here to identify bridging themes
that can help to integrate a mixed literature on
the neuropsychological and neurobiological ba-
sis of ADHD in our sketch of the elements of
an integrative model. Viewing ADHD in terms
of these elements of cognitive control may
help to simplify and cut across the many, re-
lated conceptions of how self-regulation breaks
down in this disorder from a neuroscience per-
spective. The basic assumption of this model
is that learning when, what, and in which con-
texts to expect an event, is critical for the
child in planning and maintaining appropriate
thoughts and actions in different contexts over
time. Adjusting behavior when these expecta-
tions are violated is an essential element of
cognitive control, which presumes that the abil-
ity to accurately create these predictions is
intact and mapped effectively onto the current
context. Deficits in learning to detect regular-
ities or irregularities in the environment could
lead to less recruitment of cognitive control.
This weakness could have a cascade effect
during early development such that many as-
pects of regulatory control become affected.
Likewise, poor cognitive control could lead to
problems altering behavior when irregulari-
ties or violations in the environment occur. By
examining the longitudinal progressions and
individual variation observed within the dis-
order of ADHD, we may be better able to
delineate neural systems and psychological
mechanisms in pathways to ADHD, in its sub-
types, and in related conditions with which it
often overlaps.

